Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Air Mauritius and New Mauritius Hotels Rise

-- B y   K a m l e s h   B h u c k o r y
-- 
2011-02-11T16:40:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-11/sub-saharan-african-stocks-air-mauritius-and-new-mauritius-hotels-rise.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index rose for a
second day, climbing 0.6 percent to 78.55 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi and paring its decline this week to less than 0.1
percent, a third of decreases.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index rallied to the highest since
February 2008, adding 1.1 percent to 2,062.01 by the 1:30 p.m.
close in Port Louis. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index
climbed 0.3 percent to 26,682.62 by 2:34 p.m. in Lagos,
extending its drop this week to 0.3 percent. Namibia’s
FTSE  Namibia Overall Index  snapped three days of declines,
rising 2.1 percent to close at 918.78 by 5 p.m. in Windhoek.  The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index retreated for the
first day in three, losing 0.2 percent to close at 1,054.18 by 3
p.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.    Air Mauritius Ltd . (AML MP), sub-Saharan  Africa ’s fourth-
biggest airline, jumped to the highest level since June 2008,
adding 3 rupees, or 13 percent, to 22 rupees. Profit for the
third quarter through September surged almost fourfold 12.5
million euros ($17 million) as it carried more passengers and
cargo, it said yesterday.    New Mauritius Hotels Ltd . (NMH MP), the country’s largest
leisure operator by market value, climbed the most since June
2009, rallying 6 rupees, or 5.4 percent, to 118 rupees. Net
income for the first quarter through December advanced 10
percent to 568 million rupees ($19 million), it said in a
statement published on the bourse’s website today.  Separately, the company’s recommendation was raised to
“accumulate” from “hold” at Cim Stockbrokers Ltd., according
to an e-mailed statement from the Port Louis-based brokerage
today.    UT Bank Ltd . (UTB GN), a Ghanaian lender, rose the most in
3 1/2 months, gaining 2 pesewas, or 7.7 percent, to 28 pesewas  “UT’s full-year profit for 2010 is expected to rise
between 20 and 25 percent over the previous year,” Hilary
Lomotey, a trader with  Renaissance Capital , said in a telephone
interview from Accra. The results will be distributed next week,
he said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
